Artist in Residence • Lúnasa• 2023•
Inis Oírr

Song collector Tom Munnelly once said ‘Traditional singing is an art of intimate communication, not public declaration. The kitchen not the concert hall is its natural milieu, and the location wherein it evolved’ 

(Munnelly 2001, Journal of Music ) 

But more importantly, the continuity of the tradition rather than its physical location is the maintenance of its ethos.

With that ethos in mind, I have had the great privilege to have spent a very focused wonderful residency on Inis Oírr, at Áras Èanna, to carry out some folklore work and research on the local stories of Island storyteller Joe Mháirtín Ó Flaithearta and link it to my ongoing song research and Nightvisiting work. 

The experience was deeply enriching. So many beautiful vivid stories, and songs in a place that is ancient, still and beautiful and full of dexterous language and lyricism. I have been surrounded by so much beauty; Stone walls, milky air, whistling wind dancing outside the Áras, ink black starry skies and boreens that envelope you. I imagine the island storyteller in 1950’s Inis Oírr, using the long dark autumnal nights to draw in a crowd, and sometimes a collector straight out of a currach, to tell a story to, and speak a song to . Electricity reached the Aran Islands in 1975.

The work of Áras Éanna as an artists homeplace and a centre for creating, making, researching and performing is very important and hugely special. To be immersed , to be surrounded by the landscape, the islanders and the residency itself allows for immersion. 
Tom Munnelly the collector once worked in a knitwear factory.  I’m sitting in what was once a knitwear factory on the island and I’m grateful for this time to make, imagine and culminate my ongoing research. 

I hope I can share it with you all along the way as we continue down the boreens to go Nightvisiting with the project into 2023 and 2024. 

Thank you Dara, thank you Aisling, thank you Áras Éanna, áit an-speisíalta agus tá gliondar i mo chroí a bheith anseo. 

Ag tnúth go mór ag teacht ar áis, back soon x

‘When the people had the days work done they used to go to their neighbours house next door or maybe a good distance away and there they talked about different things for three or four hours around the hearth or played cards which was a common pastime for a few hours. Sometimes a dance was generally opened up by the best step dancer. Then probably a jig was danced and a famous dance called “ the rakes of mallow “ which was danced by four girls and four boys. Then the “ quadrilles “ which was generally danced by two pairs a side and two pairs top and bottom. The people would return about ten o clock and if the music was good and the amusements satisfactory they would stay on until eleven o’clock on a good Summers evening’.

-Cannon Street Meath 1936 

This Friday Nightvisiting travels to Liverpool for its first UK performance! It has been a wonderful collaboration with Liverpool University and the School of Irish Studies who have nourished this collaboration alongside The Liverpool Irish Festival. 

To perform Nightvisting in the remarkable Yoko Ono • Lennon, Tung Auditorium in Liverpool this week is an iconic moment for the music the song and the stories that are voiced in the show. To hear them dance, echo and reverb around this space will be very special and to take it to a wider audience and diaspora, also a special moment. 

There are so many friends and family travelling to join us on Friday. To each of you , thank you. To Tim, Claire and Mike, thank you for being part of this journey and for celebrating with me my love of the old songs and folklore. You are musical alchemists of great talent and brilliance with big hearts.

Presented by Poetry Ireland @poetryireland and UNESCO Dublin City Of Literature, I am delighted to be sharing my voice in song with Steve Cooney for this special event; 
Dub-Lines, a very special celebration of the late and much-loved poet Brendan Kennelly with poets Paula Meehan, Rachael Hegarty, writer and filmmaker @alangilsenan, TCD colleague and poet, Gerald Dawe, poet Katie Donovan, poet Gerard Smyth and friend Des Geraghty as they read his poems and explore his legacy @moli_museum 12th November

• Liverpool •

Nightvisiting 
Yoko Ono Lennon Auditorium
October 20th 2023

•Old Traditions in New Spaces•

Nightvisiting came to Liverpool for its first performance in the UK, paying homage to the resilience of the music and stories that came to Liverpool and to those that carried them, and carry tradition to this day. 

We went rambling down the boreens with a SOLD OUT show in the heart of Liverpool in what is one of the most beautiful spaces to sing and perform in. I could feel Yoko and John gently holding space with us. My heart is full of the music made and the songs shared. 

Buíochas ó chroí to fellow artists @clairesherrymusic @timdoylemusic & @mikebrookfieldguitar who weaved their unique magic and to all those who went Nightvisiting. To the Institute of Irish Studies, Liverpool Irish Festival and to those who sang, and raised the roof and those who stayed to share a story or two with me : Thanks to you 🤍

More to come soon x 

📸 Roger Sinek

You’ll Deliver Christmas 

🎄

Nightvisiting 

We welcomed in 2023 right here in Gortalassa Old School house Sheep’s Head Peninsula West Cork. I was just off a flight from London performing at the National Theatre for 4 months and to come home to folklore song and stories was the best way to embrace a new year. Now on December 16th we close what has been a phenomenal year of Nightvisits, right back where we started! The final Nightvisiting show of 2023 is sold out on December 16th at Gortalassa Old School house, and I can’t wait to bring you a very special Christmas Edition of Nightvisiting with @clairesherrymusic @mikebrookfieldguitar @timdoylemusic and our special guest @wayne.p.sheehy 

Thanks to each and every one of the venues, patrons, friends, community, guests and musicians who joined me this year. It’s been very special to be in your company, and to sing and share this material. I am grateful too to all the old ghosts who walked the boreens with us and lit the way. 
This is just the beginning for Nightvisiting and I’m excited to share what 2024 brings with you  soon! 

Thanks Ramblers. You make it special x
